column2:
Hi there, this project seems promising, but I'm having a really difficult time getting it set up using the docker-compose method. I have encountered several typos and unexpected errors along the way.

Particularly, the username and password used to setup Mongo and then access it from the API and from the Jenkins build collector don't seem to match up. Is the master branch supposed to work out of the box? I looked at and followed the documentation multiple times. Any help is appreciated.

Just for a start, I'm trying to get Hygieia running with just Jenkins, but the Jenkins container keeps complaining about Mongo auth failing. It appears that Mongo installs and runs with no blank username and password by default. But the `config/hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties` file was using a password. I have confirmed Mongo isn't using a password by trying to log into the Mongo container with a username and password, and it's denied. In the above mentioned file, I have tried blank creds:
```
#Database Username - default is blank
dbusername=''

#Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=''
```
and also just commented out the fields
```
#Database Username - default is blank
#dbusername=''

#Database Password - default is blank
#dbpassword=''
```
but to no avail.

If anyone can share a link to a "working" branch, it would be much appreciated.
column5: Doesn't work out of the box?
column11: 369275852 @matthewbeasley can you setup a time with @ianrossi on gitter.im or google hangout and help with some of the issues. You can include me in the call if needed. Thanks. satishc1 369300491 @ianrossi - Do you have gitter.im? If so, I will message you directly on gitter.im to coordinate a meeting. matthewbeasley 369372268 @matthewbeasley Yes, I'm on gitter.im, thanks. ianrossi 369375059 @ianrossi - can you reach out to me there in a one-to-one conversation when you get a chance? I'm available any time. matthewbeasley 369380192 I searched for you but didn't find you. Perhaps you can reach out to me. On Wed, Feb 28, 2018, 3:39 PM matthewbeasley wrote: > @ianrossi - can you reach out to me there > in a one-to-one conversation when you get a chance? I'm available any time. > > — > You are receiving this because you were mentioned. > Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub > , > or mute the thread > > . > ianrossi 365062280 @ianrossi - the username and password that is set up when creating the db can be found [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/db/db-setup.js), this is reflected in the docs. In order to run the jenkins collector, rename this [file](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/docker-compose.override.example.yml) to docker-compose.override.yml and add the environment vars for the collectors you want to run (jenkins-build for example). You can find the env vars available to you [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/build/jenkins/docker/jenkins-build-properties-builder.sh). Our docker setup is currently a work in progress and you can expect it to change in the near future. matthewbeasley 365062768 @ianrossi - if this solves your problem to your satisfaction, please close this issue. matthewbeasley 365302370 @matthewbeasley This doesn't solve my problem. For now, I have left the docker-compose setup behind and have built the JARs on a Virtualbox VM and am running each individual process. I now have Mongo running, the API, gulp serve (UI) and the Jenkins build collector (against a local Dockerized Jenkins with 2 jobs) running and all logs seem to be running with no errors. However, I can't get anything to show up in the dashboard. I'm stuck on this: ![screen shot 2018-02-13 at 10 18 56 am](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/103247/36157395-b0a6b3f8-10a7-11e8-9f91-aea2c086545a.png) First, **what does the format ` : ` mean?** I don't see any info in the docs about this. The gentlemen that posted [this video](https://youtu.be/Iq8M3llEp0k?t=1239) (over a year ago) doesn't show any special format for the job names, it's just the Jenkins job names. The logs for the build collector show this: ``` 2018-02-13 10:24:00,024 INFO c.c.d.collector.DefaultHudsonClient - Fetching jobs 0/2 pageSize 1000... 2018-02-13 10:24:00,035 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Fetched jobs 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,036 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - New jobs 0 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,044 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - New builds 0 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,051 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - New configs 0 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,052 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Finished 0s ``` Previous reports like this showed when the `New jobs` were added. But what does this mean? The jobs should now be discoverable? Because they don't come up when I search in the above screenshot. I also keep on getting the [JWT error](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1564) which makes things more difficult. Can anyone point me a to a known working walkthrough of how to get Hygieia set up in its current state? I have implemented a whole lot of different open source project from Chef to Sensu to Kubernetes and I'm kind of surprised that a project like Hygieia with Cap One behind it does not have better documentation. However, this is just an observation. Based what I've seen in screenshots, Hygieia looks to be a fantastic tools with lots to offer. Any help is very much appreciated. ianrossi 365320974 @ianrossi - can you be more specific as to how what I said doesn't solve your problem? The ui, api and mongo should start up with just `docker-compose up -d`. If this isn't the case please let me know. The JWT error is more than likely a cookie issue. If using chrome: go to [cookies](chrome://settings/siteData), search your cookies for localhost and delete that cookie. Should be good to go. This will happen when you go from the docker setup to running the jars AND your jwt has expired. If that doesn't solve your JWT issue then you need increase your jwt expiration time in your api settings. It's not clear to me exactly which issue you are experiencing but I'm confident that one of these two things will fix you up. ` : ` corresponds to your jenkins server and the name of the job you are trying to track, respectively. matthewbeasley 365323482 @ianrossi - also as far as the docs go -- hang tight. We are working to improve them. If you have specific suggestions then please air them out here as we'd love to hear your feedback. matthewbeasley 365323747 @ianrossi - actually don't air them out here lol. If you have the time and have specific suggestions, open a new issue. matthewbeasley 365326190 @matthewbeasley Thanks. I know how to solve the JWT issue, I was just sharing the observation because it makes things difficult. About the server name, I still need more clarification. > : corresponds to your jenkins server and the name of the job you are trying to track, respectively. What does "jenkins server" mean? Is this the DNS name/address of the Jenkins server? If you can give an example, that would be great. Thanks. ianrossi 365330093 @ianrossi - if you know how to solve the JWT issue then you shouldn't be seeing it. "jenkins server" does mean DNS name / address. If you are running jenkins locally in docker and exposing the appropriate port (8080 for instance) then Server name is `localhost:8080`. This should be available to you as a dropdown item though. Can you post your jenkins collector property file? It seems that you don't have that correctly configured. matthewbeasley 365338402 @ianrossi - You can assign nickname or nicename for jenkins instances so that when data is collected from multiple instances, you will know the jenkins instance - job relation. You can do it in 2 ways. 1) You can set below values in jenkins.properties (pull-based mechanism) jenkins.servers[0]=http://localhost:8080/ jenkins.niceNames[0]= give some nick name for 8080 - lets call it **ianrossi8080** You can specify multiple server instances and nicenames with index. 2) If you have Hygieia jenkins plugin installed on your jenkins instance you will see Global Hygieia settings under - Jenkins -> Manage Jenkins -> configure system -> Global Hygieia Publisher Settings (Push-based mechanism) You can refer https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/gh-pages/pages/hygieia/hygieia-jenkins-plugin/hygieia-jenkins-plugin.md on how to build *.hpi file (Hygieia Jenkins Plugin) and install plugin to Jenkins instance. Pull based mechanism - When you start running Jenkins collector, jobs/build information is pulled to Hygieia and you should be able to search basing on 1) job name only ( here my job name is HygieiaPublic) 2) nicename : jobname ( Eg - nireesh : hyg) - it should match on partial search. We used ':' as a delimiter for nicename and job name. So if you want to search on both, make you include : in between. nireeshT 365671959 Hi @nireeshT CC @matthewbeasley Thanks for this info. Is the Jenkins / Hygieia plugin required for the Jenkins build collector to work? From your post, it almost looks like the "nice names" cannot be used without the plugin. I'm working on getting the plugin working with my local Jenkins. ianrossi 365823036 @ianrossi you can either use Jenkins build collector or hygieia plugin. Just a matter of how you want to collect data. nireeshT 367724499 @ianrossi - Tomorrow we will close this issue due to inactivity. Is everything good for you? matthewbeasley 367784304 @matthewbeasley I'm all set. Thx. ianrossi 368021757 @matthewbeasley @nireeshT There is still a problem with the Jenkins build collector. column2:
Hi,

On days the sprint ends, the feature widget for Jira displays all 0's for all values regardless if displaying hours, story points, or issue count. 

Is this expected behavior? I am not sure how sprint information is gathered, but the tickets still have the "Sprint" tag for the closed sprint. I would think that displaying sprint information (regarding story points open, in-progress, and closed) would still be useful on the days a sprint ends. After the end date, perhaps displaying all 0's might be appropriate, but before and including the end date, that information still seems valid to display. 

Any help would be greatly appreciated, thank you.
column5: No Sprint data on Sprint end dates
column11:
367792933 Hi, @MarkRx @Sbrenthughes 

Just wondering if there are any possible insights into this? If this is expected behavior or not. Where is the logic for handling this? In the Jira collector, API, or does the UI handle that? Many thanks. 

To give some details regarding the issue, below are some images that I hope help describe the problem I am facing. 

This is how the feature widget appears (on days the sprint ends):
![feature](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2696304/36559397-b3260c92-17c2-11e8-902a-7c0d1ccc832a.png)

And here is a ticket that is currently "in progress", tagged with the sprint that ended (note, the sprint that just ended, is "sprint 28"):
![sprint](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2696304/36559621-663690ae-17c3-11e8-9988-bf711abc60a6.png)  e-macias
368153007 After further investigation, it appears that the logic for determining what to send the UI is applied in the API layer, specifically [FeatureServiceImpl.java](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/FeatureServiceImpl.java#L451) calls [FeatureRepositoryImpl.java](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/core/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/repository/FeatureRepositoryImpl.java#L27) to construct a query string that will determine which features belong to the current sprint.

However, it is unclear what is meant by "**_any_**" in the following statement: "A feature is part of a scrum sprint if any of the following are true: -the feature has a sprint set that has start <= now <= end and end < EOT (9999-12-31T59:59:59.999999)". Where are the "break points" of the statement, to determine if "_any_" part is true? Because it seems as if "end < EOT" will always be true. 

Yet the UI is receiving no values from the API. Looking some of the rest responses:
```
{"result":{"openEstimate":0,"inProgressEstimate":0,"completeEstimate":0,"totalEstimate":0},"lastUpdated":1519422312519}
```
and 
```
{"result":[],"lastUpdated":1519422312519}
```

By editing [FeatureRepositoryImpl's query build](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/core/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/repository/FeatureRepositoryImpl.java#L36) to evaluate 'sSprintEndDate' as less than the current date (rather than _greater than_), I can see what appears to be proper end of Sprint handling (see image below). Looking at some responses now gives:
```
{"result":{"openEstimate":6,"inProgressEstimate":12,"completeEstimate":42,"totalEstimate":60},"lastUpdated":1519422317357}
```
and
```
{"result":[{"sEstimate":"0","sEpicName":"Technical Improvements","sEpicUrl":"https://jira.com ....} 
``` 

Therefore my question now becomes, how should end of Sprint be handled? Is the change I made the correct implementation to take, or would you advice a different approach? Thanks.

**Code change**: ```{'sSprintEndDate' : {$lt : '" + currentISODateTime + "'}}```


![feature_update](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2696304/36619111-74dcab90-18a2-11e8-9f1b-92c6d088b54b.png) e-macias
368505400 Data will not show up for sprints if the sprint is over. You could change your sprint end date to be 11:59:59 and it should continue to show up the day it ends. 

If you were to make that proposed change then you would not see any data for active sprints as active sprints would be start date <= now <= end. What you have is start date <= now > end which does not make sense. MarkRx
368625186 @MarkRx, thanks for the response. I agree that my implementation is not the ideal solution. However, is there then a scenario where the "[ENDED]" tag will display?

In our current setup, there is usually about one to one-and-a-half days between sprints.  e-macias
368944535 Currently it appears to only show active sprints. I suppose the query could be changed so as to pick up the last sprint even if it is ended. MarkRx
